# Houdini TOPs Basics

If you are a generalist or tech artist that has to regularly "jump the divide" to control 3D, 2D comp, and render farm automation tasks, you will find a lot of upsides to using "data nodes" in your content creation process. These nodal operators have the capacity to expand what is possible inside a DCC package so you can quickly roll out custom workflows that allow you to take automation efforts to the next level. 

If you are talking with other 3D artists, who haven't adopted Houdini yet, the nearest competitor to what Houdini TOPs offers is an open-source program called [Gaffer](https://www.gafferhq.org/). Both tools do an amazing job at helping to tame complex tasks that would otherwise be a nightmare to manage in the long term if using a ton of cobbled together tools that lack a high-level interface.

## TOP Networks

When you are navigating through an existing Houdini ".hip" project, the TOPs (Task Operator) nodes are found in the "Tree View" window under the heading "tasks". 

![][image5]

You will typically start with a "tasks" node called "topnet1". If you double click on this node you will be brought inside this object. This is the spot in Houdini where you will build a new automation workflow.

When you look inside "topnet1" in a fresh Houdini project file, you will see a node called "local scheduler". This node is what processes TOPs data locally when you render aka cook a TOPs node graph on an individual artist's workstation. 

![][image6]

If you click inside the TOPs node graph and press the **TAB** hotkey you will see a popup contextual menu that allows you to select nodes you would like to add to the node graph.

Here is a quick list of the **TAB Menu** entries for "Files", "Images", and "Data". These nodes act as your initial entry point as you start to learn more about task operators in Houdini.

![TAB Menu](images/tops_menu.png)

The task operator nodes allow you to quickly transform media ([FFmpeg Encode Video](https://www.sidefx.com/docs/houdini/nodes/top/ffmpegencodevideo.html), [FFmpeg Extract Images](https://www.sidefx.com/docs/houdini/nodes/top/ffmpegextractimages.html)), carry out filesystem operations ([Make Directory](https://www.sidefx.com/docs/houdini/nodes/top/makedir.html), [File Compress](https://www.sidefx.com/docs/houdini/nodes/top/filecompress.html), [File Copy](https://www.sidefx.com/docs/houdini/nodes/top/filecopy.html), [File Rename](https://www.sidefx.com/docs/houdini/nodes/top/filerename.html), [File Remove](https://www.sidefx.com/docs/houdini/nodes/top/fileremove.html), etc), and run user defined command-line tasks using a [Generic Generator](https://www.sidefx.com/docs/houdini/nodes/top/genericgenerator.html) node.

Pro Tip: If you are looking for a TOPs node to move files from one folder location to another, this can be achieved with the standard [File Rename](https://www.sidefx.com/docs/houdini/nodes/top/filerename.html) node. Moving files and renaming them are functionally the same to the computer.

---

When you start to explore more complex automation workflows in Houdini, it's useful to know that you can look at the several different ways to distribute a TOPS node graph rendering (cook) operation.

When looking in the **TAB Menu**, if we navigate down to the "Schedulers" section, we can see the [other ways a Houdini TOPs node graph can be batch rendered](https://www.sidefx.com/docs/houdini/tops/schedulers.html) either locally on your workstation, or on a network connected render cluster aka a render farm.

![][image10]  

The "TAB Menu" of TOPS (Task Operator) Schedulers

The Houdini TOPs based "[HQueue Scheduler](https://www.sidefx.com/docs/houdini/nodes/top/hqueuescheduler.html)" node allows you to pass your jobs to the HQueue render manager.

If you want to get started with building your own on-prem or cloud hosted render farm, SideFX Houdini's installer provides the license free "[HQueue](https://www.sidefx.com/docs/houdini/hqueue/overview.html)" render farm management tool. There is a HQueue client and an HQueue server program available. The HQueue program is fully cross-platform compatible and it runs on macOS, Linux, and Windows. HQueue is managed using a web browser based Web UI.

If you look through the rest of the "TAB Menu \> Schedulers" menu entries, you will see an option for using the "[Tractor Scheduler](https://www.sidefx.com/docs/houdini/nodes/top/tractorscheduler.html)". This is a node that allows [Pixar's Tractor](https://renderman.pixar.com/tractor) program to act as a 3rd party render manager for rendering out Houdini .hip files. Tractor is a commercially licensed program that is provided by Pixar's RenderMan team for handling render jobs on macOS and Linux systems.

The "[Deadline Scheduler](https://www.sidefx.com/docs/houdini/nodes/top/deadlinescheduler.html)" allows you to use Amazon Web Services (AWS) [Thinkbox Deadline](https://aws.amazon.com/thinkbox-deadline/) render manager program to control your render jobs on macOS, Linux, and Windows.

## Tasks Toolbar

The controls needed to render aka cooK a TOPs node graph can be found at the top of the Task Network window:  

![][image11]

"Cancel the current cook" Button  

![][image12]

Clicking the red stop sign button icon will clear out any of the generated work units. This resets the node graphs' previous output so you can tweak things, and run a new job with your current settings.

### "Cook the output node's work item" Button

![][image13]

Clicking the orange play button icon cooks the node graph, which then creates new work units. After the work units are created, the node graph will begin processing.

## Using TOPs

Houdini TOPs (Task Operators) have a neat property where you start by defining an input parameter, such as a file pattern that matches a specific file type.

![][image14]

If you want to set a specific node to be the output of the TOPs network, click on the right hand side of the node's shape in the node graph. This will toggle on/off an orange color indicator. When the orange color is brightly visible on the node's shape it tells houdini that you want to render all upstream connected nodes, and stop at this node as the final output of the node graph.

![][image15]

This orange flag is how you define what branch of a TOPs network you want to render, and is handy for troubleshooting new workflows. When the scene is cooked, Houdini will then generate individual tasks which are also known as work units which are visible inside the node shape as small green dots:

This image shows a node with 3 work units (tasks) that it will iterate through when rendered:  

![][image16]

This image shows a node with 153 work units (tasks) that it will iterate through when rendered:  

![][image17]

These work units are then processed downstream by nodal operators that can read any of the custom attributes you define.

If you click on one of the green circle "work unit" shapes on a node, you can then inspect what that specific operation is, and find out the custom attributes that are being processed, and see a report of the active variables and their state. This is roughly similar to the concept of viewing a log file for a command-line task.

When cooking a node graph, a "wait for all" node can help to manage flow control. When this node is added to the end of a series of nodes, this will pause the node graph and wait on this branch until all work units that exist upstream are completed. This allows control over parallel vs series task execution.

One can also pass any TOPs based attributes you define to the rest of Houdini's contexts such as **out** (where ROPS render operators live), **obj** (SOPS surface operators), img (Copernicus compositing), or **stage** (Solaris OpenUSD scene graph).
